Chapter:
The &GRSYLI; package &GRSYLI; package overview
This is the manual for the &GRSYLI; package version &VERSION;.
The &GRSYLI; package contains various collections of small graphs with certain symmetry properties, and provides functionality for the access to these graphs, along with several precomputed properties for each graph available.
All of the functions in this package deal with finite graphs in &DIGRAPHS; format .
Installing &GRSYLI; &GRSYLI;
To install the &GRSYLI; package, you will need to download the most recent tar.gz file, found at &PKGWWWHOME;. Once downloaded, you can install the package by following the instructions found in the &GAP; reference manual, https://docs.gap-system.org/doc/ref/chap76.html.
The &GRSYLI; package requires the following &GAP; packages:
GAPDoc , version 1.6.6 or higher;
Digraphs , version 1.6.1 or higher.
Each of the above packages are part of the standard &GAP; distribution.
Loading &GRSYLI;
Once correctly installed, you can load the &GRSYLI; package at the &GAP; prompt by typing the following.
gap> LoadPackage("grsyli"); true
Citing &GRSYLI;
If you use the &GRSYLI; package in your research, please tell us about it by emailing rhysjevans00@gmail.com. We are interested in any research involving the use of the &GRSYLI; package and might refer to your work in the future.
If you wish to refer to the &GRSYLI; package in a published work, please cite &GRSYLI; like a journal article. The following is a BibTeX entry for the current &GRSYLI; version:
@Manual{cvt, author = {Evans, Rhys J. and Montero, Antonio and Poto\v{c}nik, Primo\v{z}}, key = {cvt}, title = {{GrSyLi -- GRaphs with SYmmetries LIbrary for GAP, Version &VERSION;}}, url = {\verb+(&PKGWWWHOME;)+}, year = {2024}
Examples of the use of &GRSYLI;
We will give a simple example of how to use the &GRSYLI; package here.
In this example, we will examine the cubic vertex-transitive graphs with 50 vertices.
gap> LoadPackage("grsyli"); true gap> gap> gap>
